# Project context — read + keep updated

This repo is a personal Supabase-backed workspace (notes + tasks + calendar + assistant). **`AGENTS.md` at the repo root is mandatory reading** — stack, routes, data model, conventions, and known gotchas all live there.

## Before you do anything

1. **Read `AGENTS.md` first** — before exploring the codebase, writing code, running migrations, or proposing architecture. No exceptions.
2. If the task touches the data model, also skim `supabase/migrations/` chronologically.
3. Follow existing patterns documented in the file — don't introduce a new state lib, routing system, or CSS approach.

## Before you commit anything

**Update `AGENTS.md` in the same commit** whenever the change would leave the doc stale. Review the doc one last time before staging — if you learned or changed something worth a future agent's time, append it now.

Triggers (same as in `AGENTS.md`):

- New/changed route, page, Zustand store, optional addon, external service, Edge Function, cron, or DB trigger
- New/changed DB table or column (also update migration + `src/types/database.ts`)
- New gotcha, convention change, or non-obvious lesson from the session

Small change → one or two lines in the relevant section. Append; don't rewrite the whole doc.

## Keep AGENTS.md alive (during work, not only at commit time)

The doc is intentionally imperfect. Treat it as a living document and **update it in the same change** whenever any of these happens:

- You add a new route, page, Zustand store, optional addon, or external service.
- You add or change a DB table/column, an Edge Function, a cron job, or a DB trigger.
- You discover a gotcha worth a future agent's time (an undocumented quirk, a footgun, a surprising integration behavior).
- You change an established convention (naming, sort order, file layout, env/secret handling).
- You learned something this session that the doc doesn't already say.

If the change is small, a one- or two-line addition to the relevant section is enough. Don't refactor the whole doc — just append.

## Other hard rules

- When you change a DB table, update the matching migration **and** `src/types/database.ts` in the same change.
- Don't commit unless the user asks. When you do, match the lowercase conventional-commit style already in `git log` (`feat:`, `fix:`, `fix(scope):`).
- Owner is on Windows + PowerShell — avoid bash-only syntax (`&&` chaining, heredocs) in shell commands. Use `;` or split commands.
- Use Tailwind tokens from the design system (`surface-*`, `text-*`, `brand-50…brand-950`); don't hard-code colors.
